\begin{align*}
y &= \frac{1}{1-a} \\
\Rightarrow \quad 1-a &= \frac{1}{y} \\
\Rightarrow \quad a &= 1 - \frac{1}{y} \\
\Rightarrow \quad f^{-1}(a) &= 1 - \frac{1}{a}
\end{align*}
Now we find the product $f^{-1}(a) \times a \times f(a)$. Substituting $f^{-1}(a)$ and $f(a)$,
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(a) \times a \times f(a) &= \left(1 - \frac{1}{a}\right) \times a \times \frac{1}{1-a} \\
&= \frac{a-1}{a} \times a \times \frac{1}{1-a} \\
&= \frac{a-1}{a} \times \frac{a}{1-a} \\
&= -1
\end{align*}
Therefore, the product $f^{-1}(a) \times a \times f(a)$ is $-1$.
